  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Surgical site infections (SSI) constitute a significant health-economic and clinical
      challenge. The investigators conducted a cluster-randomized, cross-over study to compare the
      efficacy of plain soap and water (PSW), used ubiquitously across sub-Saharan Africa for
      surgical hand preparation, to alcohol-based hand rub (ABHR), with SSI rates as the main
      outcome measure.

      A total of 3317 patients undergoing clean and clean-contaminated surgery were included in the
      study and followed up for 30 days.
    </textblock>
